  "text": "small primitives such as dots or small lines. We use our approach to warp one stippled image into another one by moving its primitives. The advantage of our approach is that it guarantees collision-free transformations ( § 2.2). We use the method of [CITATION_1] to generate particles on the source and target images. We set the method such that the number of source and target particles is the same. We solve the transport problem by assigning a unit mass to each particle. In this case, using the same number of particles with unit mass, mass transport reduces to an assignment problem and its solution does not require splitting or merging particles [CITATION_2] . In our context, it ensures that a source stipple is associated to single target particle and reciprocally. For the ground distance, we use the standard L 2 distance that generates straight lines as geodesics. For small lines, their source and target orientations are computed using the input images, and linearly interpolated between these values at intermediate frames. Our method extends the original work of [CITATION_3] that applies to still images and videos by enabling it to achieve warping between unrelated images. The results are shown in Figure 14 , with additional results shown in the video. The use of a quadratic ground distance guarantees that the displacement interpolation produces particles with minimal kinetic energy, since it minimizes the sum of the squared traveled distances and since particles have constant velocity. We numerically evaluate this property: over the telephone sequence, the greedy matching produces a kinetic energy of 899.5 units, while the displacement interpolation halves this energy to 447.0 units. ",
